"Yes, sir. You should be on your way by now, they were still in the mess hall to pick up their rations."         At exactly 0500, the Exodus Company assembled at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We will be relocated to the forward operating base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and the later attack on Ianlos in order to drive out the rebels. There we will establish a base camp at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "March to your squads and mount up."
The company broke up into their respective squads, and the soldiers were distributed by the corporals onto the tanks. Cohren climbed onto one of the tanks further ahead in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith and two new recruits. Cohren remembered the arrival of the two a few days ago, but knew little about them. He sat sideways and let his legs swing while he adjusted his backpack and the radio set, which was connected to his headset and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?" Nemic asked after they had settled in.
"Do you mean the rooster he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning when they let the animal go on a farm. "Yes, I think so."
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he could make out the movement of a small rooster, searching the surroundings by constantly turning its head.
"Yes, he's still with him," Cohren replied as the tank's hatch opened and the commander came into view.
"All tanks move out," the commander spoke slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the convoy of tanks and Strykers roared as they set into motion. The Kronos tank, which Cohren was riding in, jolted as the brake was released and they joined the formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania plain. Due to the winter storms, the swamps had frozen and the forests were snow-covered, nevertheless, the mud was omnipresent.
After about an hour, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, right?"
"Yes, Operation Firestorm," Cohren replied. "We thought the matter would be wrapped up in a few weeks, but we underestimated them."
"Underestimated is a strong understatement," Nemic interjected into the conversation. "We were not prepared for their arsenal of weapons and the number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only last month the Erebus. We should have even seen them on our way."
"I stand firmly on the side of the Federation," Orson said defiantly. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"That's what you say now. But I've seen that most of the eighteen-year-old recruits like you quickly take cover as soon as they hear a shot," Craith explained.
"We'll see about that," Cohren said laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We are receiving heat signatures, about 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren climbed up onto the tank and put on his specialized glasses. As he switched them to "thermal imaging," he could recognize the signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," Cohren replied through his throat microphone.
"Are they hostile?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"I can't tell," Cohren replied. He reached for his microphone and said, "Exodus Company, hold fire until under fire. Lure them out."
As they approached, the point-like heat signatures took shape. As they came even closer, one of them hurried off to get something. Immediately, she returned to the small hill where the others were. The figures lay on the ground, they took up firing positions.
"We have enemy contact," Shaw shouted over the radio as orange tracer rounds were fired from the hill. While the tanks came under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket zoomed past and hit behind the formation, exploded, and scattered debris and rubble onto one of the tanks. Another struck sideways into a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition went off in the air.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees to the right, 300 meters. Fire," shouted the commander of the tank column over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flew toward the hill and exploded, sending dirt and rock into the air.
"Send the Sentis in," shouted Knoxx, who was observing the hill with a pair of binoculars. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened and an unarmed soldier came out, wearing a special headset. He gave orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, stormed out. Swinging their thin, metallic arms and legs forward, they began to sprint. They carried their weapons on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" Craith asked as he watched.
"Looks like capture," Cohren guessed as the two Sentinels disappeared into the ash and smoke cloud. Screams and gunfire echoed from the hill, but quickly fell silent. A short time later, the two Sentinels returned and dragged someone behind them, whose boots left tracks in the ground. After they had returned to the cover of the column, they threw the figure to the ground. She groaned in pain as she landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw went to the figure who was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, Sir," the Sentinel replied. "The rest fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. "Get rid of this guy for me!"
